{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"Mirror how validity is produced, but enforce independence STRUCTURALLY: score novelty in a\nSEPARATE Pass-2 structured sub-call that ALONE receives the prior findings and answers a\nsmall novelty sub-answer set (\"does this finding correspond to a prior finding?\"). The\nexisting verification sub-call (severity attributes + binary/validity) receives NO prior\nfindings, so the `verify.py:64` independence invariant (VERIFIER_RULES[0]) holds by\nconstruction. Pass-1 stays unanchored.\n\nThis is NEW behavior (pure creation): `discriminates_novelty`, `NOVELTY_EXPECTS`, the\n`novelty` contract, the novelty prompt, and the dedicated novelty eval spec do not exist\nyet — none are edits to existing symbols.\n\n## Why an LLM sub-call and not the deterministic `sidecar.norm_id` fingerprint\n\n`sidecar.norm_id` (`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py:119`) is an EXACT-match key (a\nsignificant-token set + criteria): it collapses reordering/punctuation but a carryover\nfinding RE-PHRASED across a plan edit (different significant tokens) mints a different\n`norm_id` and would slip through as \"novel\". The whole point of novelty is to catch the\nSUBSTANTIVELY-same finding reworded between reviews, so an LLM matches-prior sub-call is the\nright tool. `norm_id` remains the offline join key; novelty is the runtime carryover signal.\nIndependence is still enforced STRUCTURALLY (the separate sub-call), not by prompt assertion.\n\n## Novelty sub-answer set + scoring arithmetic (canonical)\n\nNovelty is the INVERSE of \"matches a prior finding\". The sub-call answers a small set of\nfactual **matches-prior** questions (yes / insufficient / no), each scored on the same\nordinal map Pass-3 uses for validity (`yes=1.0, insufficient=0.5, no=0.0`):\n\n- Q1 `restates_prior_defect` — Does this finding restate the same underlying defect as a\n  specific prior-review finding?\n- Q2 `cites_prior_location` — Does it cite the same plan location/section as that prior finding?\n- Q3 `matches_prior_fix` — Is its suggested remediation substantively the same as that prior\n  finding's?\n\nA named constant `NOVELTY_SUBANSWERS = (\"restates_prior_defect\", \"cites_prior_location\",\n\"matches_prior_fix\")` in `decide.py` (the analogue of `GRADED_BINARY`) anchors the\n`novelty_model` fields to the scoring arithmetic so they can never name different questions.\n\n`carryover_match = mean(answerable matches-prior sub-answers)` (a sub-answer is \"answerable\"\nwhen it is one of yes/insufficient/no; a missing/blank one is skipped); **`novelty = 1 −\ncarryover_match`** ∈ [0,1]. High novelty (≈1.0) = no prior match (genuinely new); low novelty\n(≈0.0) = carryover. If NO sub-answer is answerable, novelty defaults to **0.0** (carryover →\nnever dropped — the safe direction). The questions are FACTUAL (match-prior), never normative\n(\"should I downrank\"). Pass-3 maps novelty deterministically in task cc5b.\n\n## The `novelty` contract (registered alongside `verification`)\n\nA distinct registered structured-output contract — `novelty_model` in `verify.py`, registered\nunder the kernel name `novelty`, with `plan_review_novelty` registered as the plan-review\nalias in `passes.py` (mirroring how `verification`/`plan_review_verification` pair). Per-item\nfields: `index: int`, the three matches-prior sub-answers (default `\"insufficient\"`, mirroring\nthe verification Binary defaults), and `matched_prior_id: str` (default `\"\"` — the prior\nfinding id this matched, or empty when there is no match). The existing `verification`\ncontract is NOT reused (it has no prior-findings input). There is no schema \"prompt id\" field —\nthe prompt is identified by its prompt-library id (`plan-review-novelty`), not a payload field.\n\n## The sub-call mechanism + data-flow contract\n\n`verify.py` gains `score_novelty(findings, *, prior_findings, run_chunk, …) -> {index:\nnovelty_float}` mirroring `verify_findings`: it injects the prior findings as context to the\nSEPARATE novelty sub-call (the only call that sees them), reshapes by global index, and maps\neach finding's sub-answers to a novelty via `decide.novelty(...)`. The returned\n`{index: novelty}` map is what cc5b's Pass-3 consumes; an index absent from the map (the\nfinding had no novelty produced) is treated by cc5b as carryover (novelty 0.0). The\nseverity/validity sub-call and Pass-1 are NOT given the prior findings.\n\n## Fallback (fail-safe — never silently suppress)\n\nIf the novelty sub-call errors, times out, or returns malformed/unparseable output, novelty\ndefaults to **0.0** for the affected findings (treated as carryover → enforced at the normal\nthreshold, NEVER dropped). A broken novelty signal can only make the gate STRICTER, never\nsuppress a finding. The fallback emits a WARN log (so an elevated fallback rate is observable)\nand is covered by a FakeRunner test in `tests/unit/test_plan_review_novelty.py` (a sub-call\nthat raises / returns junk → every novelty is 0.0).\n\n## `discriminates_novelty` eval gate — in a DEDICATED spec (the bar; resolves the BLOCK)\n\nThe novelty sub-call uses its OWN prompt + contract, NOT the `plan-review-verifier` prompt — so\nits eval cases and scorer go in a **dedicated** `src/rebar/llm/eval_specs/plan-review-novelty.eval.yaml`\nkeyed to `prompt: plan-review-novelty` (appending them to the verifier spec would score the\nverifier prompt's output, which never carries novelty — the wrong artifact). Add a\n`discriminates_novelty` deterministic scorer mirroring `discriminates_true_from_false` /\n`discriminates_impact_levels` (`eval_scorers.py`): a PER-CASE boolean at the **0.5 midpoint** —\na `kind: novel` (`expect: high_novelty`) case must score novelty **≥ 0.5**; a `kind: carryover`\n(`expect: low_novelty`) case **< 0.5**. The scorer reads the novelty score via a dedicated\n`_novelty(out)` extractor (numeric `novelty`, else computed from the matches-prior sub-answers\nvia the shared `decide.novelty` arithmetic, so the scorer and the gate can never diverge).\nRegister `discriminates_novelty` in the `eval_scorers.REGISTRY` and add ≥ 3 labeled\n(prior-finding, new-finding) carryover/novel pairs (both directions) to the dedicated spec.\n\n`eval_scorers.ALLOWED_EXPECTS` is extended with `NOVELTY_EXPECTS = {high_novelty, low_novelty}`\nAND `validate_dataset_and_gold` in `eval.py` gains a novelty-axis balance check analogous to\nthe validity/impact ones (if any `NOVELTY_EXPECTS` value is used, BOTH `high_novelty` and\n`low_novelty` must be present), so `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` both accepts the cases and\nstill enforces a balanced discrimination set.\n\n**The bar (numeric target):** the scorer is GATED by the spec-level convention already used by\nthe sibling discriminators — `gate: at_least(2)` over `epochs: 3` with `coverage_threshold: 0.8`\n(i.e. every labeled novelty pair discriminated correctly at the 0.5 midpoint in ≥ 2 of 3\nepochs). There is no separate AUC/F1 number: house style for deterministic discriminators is\nthe per-case 0.5 midpoint + the spec gate (the llm-judge `threshold:` field does NOT apply to\ndeterministic scorers). This eval bar is DISTINCT from the runtime drop threshold\n`T_novel = 0.7` (task cc5b): 0.5 is \"did the scorer separate novel from carryover at all\"; 0.7\nis \"how novel must a finding be to be eligible for the Pass-3 drop\".\n\n## The evidence gate (enforcement lives in cc5b)\n\n\"cc5b must not activate the drop rule until this bar is met\" is enforced in cc5b, not here: the\nPass-3 drop rule ships behind a config key that is **default-OFF** for v1 (expand-contract), so\nthe deterministic floor is inert until the novelty discriminator has cleared the bar and the\nkey is flipped. 150b's responsibility is to make the scorer + labeled set + the dedicated spec\nexist and validate; cc5b consumes them.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Novelty scored in a separate Pass-2 sub-call that alone sees prior findings (`src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/verify.py` `score_novelty`, re-exported in `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py`)\n- [ ] The severity/validity sub-call receives NO prior findings; Pass-1 receives none\n- [ ] Novelty sub-answers are factual (match-prior), not \"should I downrank\"; a `NOVELTY_SUBANSWERS` constant in `decide.py` anchors the fields; `novelty = 1 − mean(answerable matches-prior sub-answers)` on the `yes=1.0/insufficient=0.5/no=0.0` map; no answerable sub-answers → novelty 0.0\n- [ ] Fail-safe fallback: novelty sub-call error/timeout/malformed → novelty = 0.0 (carryover; never dropped) + a WARN log; covered by a FakeRunner test in `tests/unit/test_plan_review_novelty.py`\n- [ ] A distinct registered `novelty` contract (`novelty_model` in `verify.py`; `plan_review_novelty` alias in `passes.py`): `index`, the three matches-prior sub-answers (default `insufficient`), `matched_prior_id` (default `\"\"`). The `verification` contract is NOT reused\n- [ ] `discriminates_novelty` scorer (per-case, 0.5 midpoint) + a dedicated `_novelty(out)` extractor + ≥ 3 carryover/novel labeled pairs in a DEDICATED `src/rebar/llm/eval_specs/plan-review-novelty.eval.yaml` (`prompt: plan-review-novelty`) + registered in `eval_scorers.REGISTRY` (NOT appended to `plan-review-verifier.eval.yaml`)\n- [ ] `ALLOWED_EXPECTS` extended with `NOVELTY_EXPECTS = {high_novelty, low_novelty}` AND `validate_dataset_and_gold` in `eval.py` extended with a novelty-axis balance check (both poles required), so `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` accepts AND balances the new cases\n- [ ] The bar is `gate: at_least(2)`/`epochs: 3` + `coverage_threshold: 0.8` on the novelty pairs (the framework idiom; NOT an AUC literal), distinct from the runtime `T_novel=0.7`\n- [ ] The novelty scorer + dedicated spec exist and validate (`rebar prompt eval plan-review-novelty`); the drop rule remains inert (default-OFF, enforced in cc5b) until the bar is cleared — the evidence gate\n\n## Data flow to downstream (cc5b)\n`score_novelty` returns `{finding_index: novelty}` (∈ [0,1]); cc5b's Pass-3 reads it, treats an\nabsent index as carryover (0.0), and applies the deterministic floor. Novelty never re-enters\nthe severity/validity sub-call (independence). The structural-independence design decision is\nrecorded in the ADR + docs delivered by task 4cb9."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782780928399538001,"uuid":"c279f303-29f4-457b-99c0-04584e61a685"}